1. d4 d5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bf4 e6 4. e3 { White continues with normal development, but this allows the pin. } 4... Bb4 { [%cal Gb4e1] } 5. Bd3 { The most common move. White develops while fighting against Ne4. } (5. Ne2 { Defends c3, but also blocks in the bishop. } 5... O-O 6. a3 Be7! { Since capturing on c3 would not create doubled pawns, we simply retreat and leave the knights to contemplate their life decisions. Next up is c5. } { [%cal Gc7c5] }) (5. a3 { Not very logical, as we wanted to take on c3 anyway. } 5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 c5 { Followed by more pressure on c3. } { [%csl Rc3][%cal Gd8a5,Ga5c3] }) (5. Nf3 Ne4 { It's already difficult for White to defend c3. } { [%csl Rc3][%cal Ge4c3,Gb4e1] }) 5... c5 { Striking in the center immediately. } 6. dxc5 Nbd7! { [%cal Gd7c5] } 7. Ne2 (7. Nf3 Nxc5 { Since White didn't defend c3, we keep the bishop on b4. } 8. O-O Bxc3 { Creating doubled isolated pawns. } 9. bxc3 O-O { We can look forward to playing against the weak pawns. } { [%csl Rc3,Rc2] } 10. Bg5 Nce4 11. Bxe4 dxe4) 7... Bxc5 { Now that White defended c3, we no longer want to take, so we retreat the bishop. } 8. O-O O-O { Black stands slightly better thanks to better control of the center. We can look to increase the central control with e5 at the right moment. } { [%cal Ge6e5] } *


